[img[bread]]\nthe bread is in a sun-warmed paper bag from the bakery where you had your first date. you tear off a hard end piece. chewing, you look at a constellation of gravel-pocked scars on your knees and [[remember how they got there|d11]].
[img[shoes1]]\nshe insists you can't go home wounded and bleeding (true gallantry!), so you follow her two blocks east to her apartment. you walk your bike and she carries her board. you are grateful to have something to do with your hands. she's apologizing profusely for providing the vehicle of your demise. you tell her you kind of hope they leave cool scars so you can say you got them skating.\n\nyou take your shoes off in her entryway and pad back a plant-laden hallway to a pink-hued bathroom. affixing a bandaid to your elbow, she asks if you want to hang out and watch a movie. \n\nan hour later, her fingers spider across the couch to tangle with yours. she doesn't even mind that you smell [[clinical from the peroxide bubbling on your knees|six]].
[img[marm]]\nthe delicate glass jar of marmalade glows amber in the golden hour light. a vial of sunshine. a fraying patch of gingham is wrapped in twine around its lid, and its label bares the ripple of a wet thumbprint on ink. the epitome of farmer's market artisanal charm. your girlfriend always jokes with the farm kids running the stand, tousling the little ones' bowlcuts. she always leaves with her arms heaped with rainbow chard and wildflower bouquets [[and honeyed smears of marmalade across her mouth|d31]].
[img[thermos]]\nthe thermos of tea is scalds your palms and the floral steam makes your glasses fog. you peer at her over its green plastic mug as you drink, [[remembering the first time she brewed you a cup|d21]].

[img[skate]]\nshe rolls into the bakery parking lot on a skateboard. impossibly cool. you've seen photos of her skating on your phone: doing mulligans, and whoozles, and the left-handed henry. clearly, you do not know anything about skateboarding. you almost think about running away and deleting the app and living the ascetic life of a monk.\n\n"well, hey, there!" she calls to you. she takes off her helmet and her dyed pink fuzz of hair is shiny with sweat. "[[is it me you're looking for|d12]]?"\n
[img[flustered]]\n"like, are you my tinder date?" she clarifies.\n\n"um," you respond, suavely.\n\nshe fastens her helmet to a strap on her yellow backpack and tucks her skateboard under her armpit. she extends an upturned palm. the skin is shiny from a history of friction. god, she's so cool. your mouth is still open.\n\n"[[yup, you're definitely the one i'm looking for. wanna head inside?|d13]]
[img[coffee]]\nshe orders a drip coffee and a cinnamon bun. perennially stressed by on-the-spot decisions, you ask for a cappuccino, please, in a faint effort to seem cosmopolitan and cultured. she sections the pastry into halves without even asking (gallant of her). you dump one, and then two, paper packets of sugar into the delicate ceramic cup curled steaming in your palm (goofus of you).\n\ntwo hours of easy conversation pass. the cold dregs of your cappuccino are clotted thick with sugar. you don't notice until she tells you, later--running her thumb across her lower lip, wet with your spit, then brushing down the bridge of your nose--that your whole face is freckled across with brown specks of dried foam.\n\n"[[would you like to head out and try my board|d14]]?"

"pretty much always."\n\nshe adjusts the chin strap of her helmet to fit your face. so close, you can smell orange zest on her breath when she says: "that's cool. i'm surprised it took you this long to mention it."\n\nflushed with bravado and the shame of your lie, you push off. as if by fate, you careen directly into the bumper of a parked station wagon, [[skinning both knees and your left elbow|d15]].
